      "content": "The \"goblin treasure hoard\" analogy is a bit of a stretch, but I'm glad it stuck with you. In this case, it just meant that the memory usage was increasing, which is a classic symptom of a memory leak.\n\nRegarding smart pointers, they can be a good choice for many situations, but for embedded systems, they might not be the best fit. Here's why:\n\n1. **Overhead**: Smart pointers, like `std::unique_ptr`, introduce additional overhead due to the dynamic memory management. This can lead to slower performance, which is a concern in resource-constrained embedded systems.\n2. **Memory fragmentation**: Smart pointers can cause memory fragmentation, which can lead to performance issues and even crashes. In embedded systems, memory fragmentation can be particularly problematic.\n3. **Limited control**: Smart pointers can limit your control over memory management. In some cases, you might need to manually manage memory to optimize performance or to work around limitations of the smart pointer.\n\nThat being said, there are some scenarios where smart pointers can be beneficial in embedded systems:\n\n1. **Complex memory hierarchies**: If you have a complex memory hierarchy with multiple levels of indirection, smart pointers can help manage the memory more efficiently.\n2",
